<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written Statement to the Commons Select Committee / Invasive Species</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the Property Care Association</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Property Care Association (PCA) is an established Trade Association that, in 2012, began working with a number of companies and individuals from the invasive weed control industry. The goal of the group was to establish trade representation and develop criteria that would improve the delivery of services and treatment outcomes for consumers, and provide lending institutions, developers and landowners with access to competent and fully vetted companies and individuals that are able to deal with invasive plants correctly and effectively. This was achieved by providing accreditation to competent contractors and developing industry standards, qualifications, guidance and insurance products that stand scrutiny and deliver consumer confidence. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Over the last two years, the PCA invasive weed group has grown and now represents approximately 25 companies. Membership includes most of the largest active and competent commercial invasive weed specialist eradication companies in the UK.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Amongst our main objectives is the aim of dispelling many of the unhelpful and misleading reports and misconceptions that surround plants such as Japanese knotweed and provide practical pragmatic information, help and advice so that invasive plants can be controlled correctly and effectively. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The balance between the different strands of the response to invasive species: detection, prevention, containment/adaptation or eradication</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is our view that the committee should understand that the established invasive weed control industry has an important role in the prevention, identification, containment and eradication of invasive plants in England and Wales. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Established specialist firms exist throughout the UK. A number of these have a wide and comprehensive knowledge of invasive weed, biology and eradication techniques. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Contractors work in partnership with commercial and domestic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and publically funded</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> clients to identify</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">control invasive plant species that are of commercial significance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in all environments. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The skills</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> experience, knowledge and reach of this important sector of commercial activity should not be overlooked.   </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 49.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The commercial invasive weed control industry has become well established, are capable and increasingly well recognized for their skills and competencies. Industry will inevitably play an active role in any solution to the invasive plant problem. It follows, therefore, that industry are willing and able to engage with legislators, policy advisors, ecologists and scientists to help forge effective policies, and play an active part in the future frameworks for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the detection, prevention, containment and eradication of invasive plant species in England and Wales</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">14 January 2014</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>